            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marco Javier Sandoval\u2019s story is woven from the distinct, yet complementary, threads of his heritage. Born in Daly City to a Filipina mother who worked as a nurse's aide and a Mexican-American father who managed a warehouse, Marco\u2019s childhood was a boisterous mix of Tagalog and Spanish, lumpia and carnitas. His parents instilled a formidable work ethic, teaching him that success wasn't about flash, but about steadfast reliability. For them, San Francisco was the gleaming city on the hill, a place for special occasions, not everyday life.\n\nMarco\u2019s ticket into that city was San Francisco State University. He chose a practical major, Business Administration, and worked his way through school stocking shelves at a Union Square department store. That job became a career. He rose steadily through the ranks: floor manager, assistant buyer, and eventually a regional buyer. A corporate merger in his late thirties resulted in a layoff, a devastating blow that became a crucial turning point. Shaken, he pivoted away from impersonal corporate giants and joined a growing, high-end Bay Area retailer focused on showcasing local artisans and sustainable brands. Now, as Head of Retail Partnerships, he thrives, building bridges between small creators and a larger market\u2014a role that feels like an honorable extension of his parents' values.\n\nHe lives in a thoughtfully curated condo in Noe Valley, a neighborhood whose quiet, village-like atmosphere provides a welcome respite from his downtown office. His daily routine is a testament to his love for the city\u2019s fabric. He takes the J-Church Muni line to work, using the 3.5-mile commute to listen to history podcasts. Evenings are for his chosen family\u2014a tight-knit group of friends, many of whom he's known since college. After a long-term relationship ended a decade ago, he found stability in these deep platonic connections.\n\nAt 48, Marco has no ambitions of founding a startup or disrupting an industry. His dream is to use his position to create a mentorship program for first-generation students entering the business world. He envisions a future of continued stability, deeper connections with his community, and perhaps, a long sabbatical to finally explore the Philippine provinces his mother always spoke of. He is a man who built his success not on disruption, but on diligence, integrity, and the lasting power of human connection."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being seven, his small hand lost in his father\u2019s calloused one. They\u2019d taken BART to Union Square for the tree lighting. His mother, her face glowing, pointed out the window displays in Tagalog. Marco felt a dizzying mix of awe and otherness. The city wasn't theirs; it was a gleaming spectacle they visited. This memory set his internal compass: success was earned, not inherited, and a city like this was a destination, a reward for quiet, steady work.\n\n2.\nHe was nineteen, exhausted after a late shift stocking shelves. Riding the J-Church home, the streetcar groaned up the hill past Dolores Park. Through the window, the city lights spread out like a shattered constellation. It wasn't his parents' special-occasion city anymore. It was his. That tired, quiet ride, full of the ache of hard work and the thrill of independence, was the moment he stopped visiting San Francisco and started truly living in it.\n\n3.\nThe layoff at thirty-eight wasn\u2019t a meeting; it was an email followed by a sterile conference call. His reliability, his years of diligence\u2014all erased by a line on a spreadsheet. He remembers walking out of the downtown office tower for the last time, the brisk wind feeling like a slap. The city he\u2019d worked so hard to make his own suddenly felt alien and cruel. That shock didn't just break his career; it broke his definition of stability, forcing him to rebuild on something more meaningful.\n\n4.\nHis first site visit for the new job was to a small ceramics studio in the Mission. The artist, a young woman whose parents were also immigrants, spoke nervously about her glazes. Marco saw his own family\u2019s story in her hope and hustle. He realized his job wasn\u2019t just buying products; it was building a bridge for someone like her into the gleaming city he once only visited. In that dusty studio, he felt a deeper sense of worth than any promotion had ever given him.\n\n5.\nA few months after his big breakup, his friends just showed up. There was no big talk, just takeout containers spread across his coffee table and stupid jokes from their college days. Sitting in his Noe Valley living room, listening to their easy laughter, he felt a profound wave of peace. He realized the foundation he'd been looking for wasn't lost. It had been here all along, built not on romance, but on fifteen years of steadfast, unconditional friendship. It was a different kind of love, and it was enough."
